column66: Our neighborhood, Waikīkī is a coming together spot for visitors and locals alike of a myriad of cultural backgrounds: itʻs a great place to meet people of all walks of life.  Our Waikīkī HPD are visible and strong supporters of keeping our neighborhood safe. It is easy to engage them and converse about local issues, both positive and negative, occurring in our neighborhood.
column67: Repeat criminal offenders (according to Representative Adrian Tam, there are actually about 85 people to whom this term applies) who continue to do harm to people and businesses here in the the Waikīkī neighborhood.  We are not talking about those whose only ʻcrimeʻ is homelessness, we are talking about those who may incidentally be homeless, but the REAL issue is their repeated actions theft and harm to people and businesses.  Second important issue: Traffic safety—most specifically pedestrian safety.  Itʻs time to truly address scofflaws, whether they are the pedestrians or the drivers. With bikes and mopeds and scooters traveling on sidewalks in Waikīkī, or along the Ala Wai Canal, pedestrians are constantly at risk for harm. For drivers who ignore traffic signals, even law-abiding pedestrians are at risk. (Note: For those pedestrians who cross against the light, this creates risks for drivers.)

column66: The desire to maintain the ʻāina, including the ocean, and to have access.   I also think that there is still a strong sense of community and wanting to slow down growth.   The pandemic and having to quarantine made us aware of how the ocean and land needed to "heal" and recover.   There was also a desire to reconnect with one another.
column67: The high cost of living as overall costs have increased, especially food and gas prices have gone up exponentially.   Affordable housing is also a major issue as finding a place is one issue and rental cost is another.   Families are being priced out of the market due to the recent increase in prices and others from the continent and internationally.   There are stories of people paying cash for houses and many non residents being the buyers.

column66: Kalama Park in Kihei is so heavily used by the community, and we enjoy it so much, especially the playground and skating rink.  The skate park desperately needs repair. We also really enjoy the public library.
column67: Public drug use, and amount of transients in the Kihei community is pretty concerning. I did see a man smoking crack out of an apple in broad daylight, in front of the kids. The encampments are full of trash, and shopping carts get left everywhere when they're done turning their cans in. There is also a huge lack of cultural influence in Kihei. It's almost like it's just catered to what a mainlander's idea of Hawaii should be, instead of what Hawaii is.

column67: Housing/property value skyrocketing out of reach of local middle class professional families who are the core of the state.  They leave because they can't afford a house, all of Hawaii suffers.  I'm embarrassed that I see a difference between locals and transplants, but I can already feel the effects of a diluted version of Hawaii. The sense of entitlement and the power of material wealth, among other things, are seeping into Hawaii.  As a lifelong resident, I am distraught to see that our keiki o ka aina are being shut out and the Hawaii as I know it is gone.  Equally distressing is our powerlessness in this tsunami.

column66: The Aloha Spirit.  Some say it is gone.  It is not.  I see it every day in places of business, in the hospital where I volunteer, and in recreational venues. The climate.  We just have nicer weather than most other parts of the world.
column67: Our gravest issue is the same here as in the rest of the world - the extreme gap between the haves and the have-nots.  Here in Hawaii we see it most clearly in the exponential growth of HOMELESSNESS.  Almost everywhere in this island you can see our brothers and sisters living out of pushcarts.   The deteriorating environment, seen in many different ways such as global warming, plastic refuse clogging the ocean, etc. is not as visible, yet, here as it is in some of the other island nations of the world, but it ought to concern us much more than it does.  It won't get better without some heavy lifting by us humans.

column66: Kaneohe is, fortunately, not completely urbanized to the extent that we've lost all semblance of being a country town. Many generations of Hawaiian families are still here. We are trying to address the inevitable "growth" intelligently, carefully and assure a harmonious integration of the "old" and the "new"

column66: Our community is farely small but majority of them have installed security systems to help keep THEMSELVES safe and to me that speaks volumes about what our little island has become!!! Everyone is to each its own so it's difficult for me to list any strengths or assets about our community!  The cost of living keeps going up because of all the big developments that our tax dollars go to pay for yet the pay checks remain the same!!! Most families have to work 2-3 jobs just to survive in their own homeland!!! Which then takes time away from our keikis!!! Most of the native people cannot even afford to buy a single home let alone afford the rent here on our little island of Maui! I won't stand here and apologies for the things that I'm seeing and feeling because these are facts and is anyone truly listening and making an honest change??? When will our government truly be FOR THE NATIVES???

column66: 1. Our community is relatively safe and there is a strong sense of pride and connection here for most people.  2. We also have good educational options - several good-quality private schools and public charter schools, and good public schools as well.
column67: 1. The cost of housing has skyrocketed. The "inventory" of housing in our community is especially low and, as a result, homes are being sold for more than they are worth, with average local families priced out for the most part OR over-extended. 2. Related to the first... there is an increase in the homeless population. Not too many families, more individuals. So we need housing and mental health services.
column94: Time - everyone works full-time and keeping up with a garden plus normal weekend kuleana and chores is a challenge. We have a small vegetable garden but its in bad shape right now.
